name: Preah Enkosei (Pr.)
dating_notes: A group of brick towers dating to the 10th century based on two inscriptions (K.262 and K. 263)(Aymonier 1901:403-407). Excavations by the Greater Angkor project in 2012 suggest possible habitation around the temples. Excavations also uncovered light post-Angkorian habitation in the form of 16-17th century Chinese tradewares (Greater Angkor Project Wat Preah Einkosei 2012). There is also a lintel at this temple that dates to this period (Polkinghorne 2007). Date also derived from analyses of inscriptions (Lustig 2009).

name: Wat Athvea
dating_notes: Wat Athvea is a 12th century temple, with similarities to Angkor Wat (Aymonier 1901: 399). There are also Post-Angkorian inscriptions dating to 1st half of the 17th century (Pou 1977: 152). Greater Angkor Project excavations in 2012 identified post-Angkorian activites, but it was difficult to document archaeologically because people still live on and use the site (Greater Angkor Project 2012). Occupation mounds were also observed nearby. See also Greater Angkor Project 2012.

dating_notes: Radiocarbon dates from a wood frame within the sanctuary dates to AD 670-780 (Uchida et al. 2008 and Data S18).  Uchida et al. were testing if the wood in these temples was original to the temples and found the radiocarbon date to support the conclusion the wood dates from the time of the temple construction in the 9th century. That this radiocarbon date pre-dates the construction date of AD 893 might be due to the "old wood" effect. There is also a lintel at this temple that dates to this period (Polkinghorne 2007) and an inscription (Lustig 2009).

name: Ta Prohm
dating_notes: Inscription K. 273 gives consecration date of 1186 CE.  Greater Angkor Project work at Ta Prohm shows multiple phases of habitation. Phase 1 (8-10th centuries CE) had light habitation. During Phases 2 and 3 (12-14th centuries CE) population is estimated at 1400-2000 people. By phase IV (13-14th century) there is only light habitation closer to the temple and no evidence for habitation post-14th century (Carter et al. 2018).

name: Angkor Wat
dating_notes: Excavation and radiocarbon data suggest the landscape and grid construction may have started in the 11th century, with most intensive habitation from late 11th to early 13th century (Carter et al. 2019). A gap in radiocarbon dates is observed between late 12th/early 13th until late 14th/early 15th century, followed by evidence for lighter post-Angkor use of the mounds from the 15th century CE (Carter et al. 2019 see also Data S18).
